        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "University President Lee Bollinger’s March 2020 announcement of Columbia’s shift to remote learning was the first of numerous unprecedented policies enacted in the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic. <b>Now, after </b><b>18 months of distanced learning, </b><b>the Columbia community has found itself in another adjustment period thanks to the return to campus.</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In advance of the fall 2021 semester, Spectator Graphics surveyed students about their social and emotional experiences since March 2020 and their outlook on returning to campus. Between Aug. 18 and Aug. 23, we received 1,362 responses from students of all class years and undergraduate colleges at Columbia. Here are their thoughts on the first fully in-person semester in a year and a half."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Diverse living experiences during the pandemic</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Without a campus to unite students in Morningside Heights, the last 18 months saw a variety of living conditions for both new and returning undergraduate students."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Though 44.9 percent of respondents resided in New York City at some point during the pandemic, the differences were stark across class years: 72.2 percent of respondents from the class of <b>2022 lived in New York City at some point in the last 18 months, while only 17.5 percent of first-years had done the same.</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "moving-in.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Overall, 79.5 percent of respondents did not live on campus in the last 18 months.</b> This includes nearly all of the first-years who did not reside in Columbia Housing and <b>approximately two-thirds of each of the remaining classes</b><b>.</b> For each class, there was a portion of students who lived in New York City at some point in the last 18-months, but never in Columbia Housing. While many of the students in this category are likely those whose primary place of residence is New York City, this percentage was particularly high for the class of 2022: 40.4 of seniors reported living in off-campus housing in the city at some point during the pandemic, while only 17.2% of first-year students reported the same."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Despite the apparent prevalence in some classes of off-campus housing, the majority (54.6%) of respondents did not live in New York City—on campus or otherwise—at any point in the last 18 months. Furthermore, 40.7 percent reported spending the entirety of the last 18 months at home. In particular, of the 535 juniors and seniors who responded to the survey, 125—23 percent—only lived at their primary residence. This group includes students in all four undergraduate schools."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Students look forward to reconnecting with each other</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Out of all of the class years, the class of 2025 reported the highest rates of feeling the fear of missing out in the last 18 months, with 81 percent of first-years responding “yes” to the question, “Have you felt FOMO (fear of missing out) at any point of the last 18 months?” These anxieties were not unique, as over 70 percent of respondents from every other class year also reported experiencing FOMO."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Respondents also rated how connected they felt to the Columbia community on a 10-point scale, with zero being “not at all connected” and 10 being “extremely connected.” The answers did not vary significantly between class years even though juniors and seniors alike spent at least a semester at Columbia prior to the onset of the pandemic. In fact, every class year rated their connectedness to Columbia between 4 and 5 on average."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Living situations generally did not have a significant effect on how connected students felt to Columbia.</b> The only exception was the small proportion of respondents who had <b>only lived away from home</b><b>—</b>the most reported rating for these students was a 2 on the 10-point scale."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "graphic-name.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The survey included space at the end for students to share any of their thoughts about the upcoming semester. Of the 208 written responses received, <b>15 percent explicitly mentioned wanting to return to in-person learning and activities for the sake of their social, emotional, and mental health</b>. In addition, only 52.2 percent of respondents felt very prepared to connect or reconnect with their college communities this semester. While some students shared anxieties about readjusting to campus, only 7.2 percent of all students who responded to the survey reported feeling extremely concerned about their social life this semester."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "graphic-name.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Meanwhile, 9.2 percent of respondents reported the highest possible level of concern regarding academics, while 22.7 percent of respondents did so when asked to rate the importance of career planning to them this semester. <b>In general, students are ready to be a part of the Columbia community and regain the social interaction afforded by an in-person semester.</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Student COVID-19 predictions are pessimistic</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "On top of housing, academic, career, and social adjustments, 68.5 percent of seniors, 60 percent of juniors, 48.7 percent of sophomores, and 54.5 percent of first years reported that they were very concerned about COVID-19 and its variants. When looking at both the mean and median of these responses per class, seniors have the highest concern out of all class years."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "graphic-name.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The University monitors the number of COVID-19 cases per day in New York City as one of the metrics for determining campus risk level and possible policy changes. Over the course of the survey, 82.4 percent of respondents predicted that the number of COVID-19 cases in New York City would have risen by Sept. 1, whereas the remaining 17.6 percent of respondents thought the numbers would fall."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "graphic-name.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "On Aug, 18, the seven-day average number of cases was <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/new-york-city-new-york-covid-cases.html\">2,018</a>, which fluctuated to <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/new-york-city-new-york-covid-cases.html\">1,954</a> cases by Aug. 23. On Sept. 1, the seven-day average number of cases was <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/new-york-city-new-york-covid-cases.html\">1,838</a>. Within our surveyed population, first-years were more optimistic about the cases in the city decreasing between the date they submitted their survey and Sept. 1st, but as most survey respondents predicted, the overall number of cases grew by <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/new-york-city-new-york-covid-cases.html\">15,932</a> between Aug. 24 and Sept. 1 while the seven-day average rate decreased."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Consistent with their predictions about increasing COVID-19 cases in New York, 76 percent of respondents predicted that Columbia’s policies regarding COVID-19 would change at some point during the semester. Only 3.3 percent predicted the policies would not change, while 20.7 percent were unsure. Since these predictions, the number of students, faculty, and staff at all Columbia facilities who tested positive for COVID-19 <b>rose to 50</b><a href=\"https://covid19.columbia.edu/content/columbia-surveillance-testing-results\"><b> cases during the week of Sept. 13 from 25 cases during the week of Sept. 6. </b></a>As of 7 p.m. on Sept. 17, Columbia placed <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2021/09/17/columbia-implements-10-person-limit-on-indoor-gatherings-restricts-residence-hall-access-to-residents-only/\">visiting restrictions</a> on its residence halls due to rising case numbers among the student population. The University has not mandated regular testing this semester for all Columbia affiliates as it did in past semesters, so the current data may not accurately represent the number of cases on campus."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Columbia’s response to COVID-19 is a continuing concern for many students</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "quotes-scrolly-1.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Accordingly, 4.3 percent of responses conveyed disappointment with Columbia’s communication and decisions made in the past 18 months and looking forward. Though Columbia tried to keep students informed through the University Life Forums on COVID-19, vaccination, and students’ fall 2021 return, 76.9 percent of respondents reported having never attended one, so this means of communication<b>—</b>even if it included valuable information<b>—</b>was largely ineffective."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "quote-highlight.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Concern over COVID-19 is not enough to keep the mandate</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "quotes-scrolly-2.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Multiple students cited the University’s requirement for vaccination as reason to relax other restrictions such as indoor masking, student and guest access to buildings, and capacity restrictions to extracurricular clubs. According to the COVID-19 resource guide, University affiliates will not be allowed on campus unless they have met the vaccine requirement or received exemption, but <a href=\"https://covid19.columbia.edu/content/faqs-regarding-covid-19-vaccination\">there will be no way</a> for individuals to verify each other’s vaccination status. The presence of vaccination exemptions was also a concern for multiple students responding to the survey."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "While responses denouncing preventative COVID-19 protocols were vastly outnumbered by opposing viewpoints, the survey results also suggest that students may be reluctant to maintain current behaviors without the Columbia Community Health Compact."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Only 43 percent of respondents would continue wearing a mask if Columbia’s mask mandate was revoked, 28 percent would not continue wearing a mask, and another 29 percent were unsure of what they would do."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "graphic-name.html"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "This distribution is generally consistent between the four class years; however, <b>the class of 2022 had the highest percentage (50.2) of respondents who would continue wearing a mask, while the class of 2024 had the highest percentage (34.8) of respondents who would not. </b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>Though the fall 2021 semester has physically reunited the Columbia community, students remain divided by their respective opinions on how to best navigate the recent return to campus. With cases on the rise and new dorm restrictions in place</b><b>, it is still uncertain whether the return to campus can be the return to normalcy that </b><b>many</b><b>we all</b><b> hope for. </b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<i>Elizabeth Commisso is a Deputy Graphics editor. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:elizabeth.commisso@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>elizabeth.commisso@columbiaspectator.com</i></a>. Follow Spectator on Twitter <a href=\"http://twitter.com/columbiaspec\">@ColumbiaSpec</a>."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "An abbreviated version of this story was published in the 2021 NSOP print edition."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "For more information about our methodology and dataset, click here."
          }
        ],
